            "subject": "LU-3057 llite: swap layout fixes - hang at sanity 56x and 56w"
          }
        ],
        "author": {
          "name": "John L. Hammond",
          "email": "john.hammond@intel.com",
          "date": "2013-04-03 20:57:05.000000000",
          "tz": -300
        },
        "committer": {
          "name": "John L. Hammond",
          "email": "john.hammond@intel.com",
          "date": "2013-04-06 19:30:47.000000000",
          "tz": -300
        },
        "subject": "LU-3048 llapi: make lfs getstripe less crashy, more correct",
        "message": "LU-3048 llapi: make lfs getstripe less crashy, more correct\n\nUse of get_param_obdvar() in get_mds_md_size() could cause the\nmax_easize param from the wrong filesystem to be read, possibly\npreventing userspace from allocating a sufficiently large buffer to\nreceive the results of the IOC_MDC_GETFILESTRIPE ioctl() and causing a\nbuffer overrun in copy_to_user().  Add internal functions\nget_param_{cli,llite,lmv,lov}() which finds the correct params for the\nfilesystem containing the path argument.\n\nIn common_param_init() the lum buffer used for IOC_MDC_GETFILESTRIPE\nis sized based on the return of get_mds_md_size().  For file systems\nwith a small number of OSTs this buffer may be too small to hold a\npath component.  Fix this by ensuring that the allocated buffer has\nsize at least PATH_MAX + 1.\n\nSigned-off-by: John L. Hammond <john.hammond@intel.com>\nChange-Id: I9847a1414cb4306f4bce5f7c30d1d1cddfab8621\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/master"
    }
  },
